'''''Black Silent Majority: The Rockefeller Drug Laws and the Politics of Punishment''''' is a non-fiction book written by [[Michael Javen Fortner]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/27/books/review/black-silent-majority-by-michael-javen-fortner.html|title=‘Black Silent Majority,’ by Michael Javen Fortner|authorlink=Khalil Gibran Muhammad|author=Muhammad, Khalil Gibran|date=September 21, 2015}}</ref>
==Overview== A look into the role of how America's drug policies impact [[African Americans]] and crime in their own neighborhoods.
==Critical reception== ''[[The New York Times]]'' said in a review of the book, "The history of black people’s ability to express and to act on their punitiveness — to be [[Law and order (politics)|tough on crime]] — is at the heart of a fascinating though severely flawed new book by Michael Javen Fortner."
