'''Pieter Wilhelm Adrianus Cort van der Linden''' (14 May 1846 – 15 July 1935) was a Dutch statesman who served as [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands]] from 29 August 1913 to 9 September 1918.

He was the last Prime Minister to lead a [[Economic liberalism|liberal]] cabinet and the last liberal to be Prime Minister until [[Mark Rutte]] in 2010 (92 years later). However, the [[First Rutte cabinet]] only held a minority in the House of Representatives. One of Cort van der Linden's major achievements was maintaining Dutch [[Neutrality (international relations)|neutrality]] during [[World War I]], although personally he was [[German Empire|pro-German]].

He also introduced [[universal suffrage]] in the Netherlands in what is nowadays known as the [[Pacification of 1917]]. Because of this, the [[Social Democratic Workers' Party (Netherlands)|Social Democratic Workers' Party]] and the [[General League of Roman Catholic Caucuses]] won the 1918 elections. The Catholic [[Charles Ruijs de Beerenbrouck]] took Cort van der Linden's place as Prime Minister.

