'''Section 8''' is a category of [[Military discharge|discharge]] from the [[United States Armed Forces|United States military]], used for a service member judged [[Mental disorder|mentally unfit]] for service. Section 8 was often given to [[homosexuals]], [[bisexuals]], [[cross-dressers]] and [[transgender people]].<ref>[[Michael Bronski]]; ''A Queer History of the United States''; </ref>
==History== The term Section 8 eventually came to mean any service member given such a discharge or behaving as if deserving such a discharge, as in the expression, "he's a Section 8". The term comes from Section VIII of the [[World War II]]-era United States Army Regulation 615-360, which provided for the discharge of those deemed unfit for military service.<ref>{{cite web|title=Office of Medical History - Neuropsychiatry in WWII, Chapter 16|publisher=United States Department of the Army|date=1963|url=http://history.amedd.army.mil/booksdocs/wwii/NeuropsychiatryinWWIIVolI/chapter16.htm|accessdate=2012-01-04}}</ref>
Section 8 discharge was often given to homosexuals, bisexuals, [[cross-dressers]] and [[transgender people]] as they were deemed mentally unfit to serve in the military. A Section 8 discharge often made it dificult for people to find work in civilian life and did not allow veterans benefits.<ref>[[Michael Bronski]]; ''A Queer History of the United States''; </ref>
Discharge under Section 8 is no longer practiced, as medical discharges for psychological/psychiatric reasons are now covered by a number of regulations. In the Army, such discharges are handled under the provisions of AR 635-200, Active Duty Enlisted Administrative Separations. Chapter 5, paragraph 13 governs the separation of personnel medically diagnosed with a [[personality disorder]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Active Duty Enlisted Administrative Separations|publisher=United States Department of the Army|date=2005-06-05|url=http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/r635_200.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2009-01-03}}</ref>
==In culture== Section 8 became a household phrase when used in the 1970s TV series ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', in which the character [[List of M*A*S*H characters#Maxwell Klinger|Corporal Klinger]] was continually seeking one (until he eventually abandoned his efforts).<ref>{{cite web|title=M*A*S*H Episode Guide - Radar's Report|publisher=The editors of TV.com|date=1973-09-02|url=http://www.tv.com/mash/radars-report/episode/43226/summary.html|accessdate=2011-02-02}}</ref> His preferred method of doing so was [[cross-dressing]].<ref>[[Nicole Markotic]]; ''Disability in Film and Literature''; 37</ref><ref>[[Douglas L. Howard]], [[David Bianculli]]; ''Television Finales: From Howdy Doody to Girls''; 238</ref> In the 2003 movie ''[[Basic (film)|Basic]]'', a DEA agent Tom Hardy (played by [[John Travolta]]) investigates a group of apparently insane mercenary Rangers turned drug dealers calling themselves Section 8.{{CN|date=November 2018}}
